The paper deals with Monte Carlo methods for matrix computations, which are commonly used in numerical analysis and scientific computing. The focus is on estimating the trace of an implicitly given matrix, which is a problem that arises in many applications. The paper provides new bounds on the number of realizations required for different probability distributions, which is a topic that falls under numerical analysis (cs.NA) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses the properties of the matrix that affect the performance of the estimators, which is relevant to data structures (cs.DS) and information theory (cs.IT). Finally, the paper presents experimental results to validate the theoretical bounds, which is a common practice in signal processing (cs.SI).
